    <div xml:id="PN376">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>vicumpi ṉītta miṟanta ñāyiṟṟup</l>
<l>pacuṅkatir maḻukiya civantuvāṅ kanti</l>
<l>ciṟunaṉi piṟanta piṉṟaic ceṟipiṇic</l>
<l>citāar vaḷpiṉeṉ ṟaṭāri taḻīip</l>
<l>pāṇa rāru maḷavai yāṉṟaṉ</l>
<l>yāṇar naṉmaṉaik kūṭṭumuta ṉiṉṟaṉe</l>
<l>ṉimaittōr viḻitta māttirai ñerēreṉak</l>
<l>kuṇakkeḻu tiṅkaḷ kaṉaiyiru ḷakaṟṟa</l>
<l>paṇṭaṟi vārā vuruvō ṭeṉṉarait</l>
<l>toṉṟupaṭu tuḷaiyoṭu paruviḻai pōki</l>
<l>naintukarai paṟaintaveṉ ṉuṭaiyu nōkki</l>
<l>viruntiṉa ṉaḷiya ṉivaṉeṉap peruntakai</l>
<l>niṉṟa muraṟkai nīkki naṉṟu</l>
<l>maravuvekuṇ ṭaṉṉa tēṟaloṭu cūṭutarupu</l>
<l>nirayat taṉṉaveṉ vaṟaṉkaḷain taṉṟē</l>
<l>yiravi ṉāṉē yīttō ṉentai</l>
<l>yaṉṟai ñāṉṟiṉō ṭiṉṟi ṉūṅku</l>
<l>mirappac cintiyē ṉirappaṭu puṇaiyi</l>
<l>ṉuḷatti ṉaḷakku miḷirnta takaiyē</l>
<l>ṉiṟaikkuḷap putaviṉ makiḻntaṉe ṉāki</l>
<l>yorunā ḷiravalar varaiyā vaḷḷiyōr kaṭaittalai</l>
<l>ñāṅkar neṭumoḻi payiṟṟit</l>
<l>tōṉṟal cellāteṉ ciṟukiṇaik kuralē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>After to some extent(?) dusk had been born, (2d-3c)</l>
<l>reddening [and] pulling in the sun that had traversed</l>
<l>the flood of the sky so that [its] fresh rays became blunt, (1-2c)</l>
<l>at the moment when bards were feeding, (5a-c)</l>
<l>embracing my Taṭāri drum with ragged straps that were tied tightly (3d-4)</l>
<l>I stood at the granary of his fertile good house. (5d-6)</l>
<l>When the moon, rising to the east, dispelled the dense darkness (8)</l>
<l>immediately in the measure that the unblinking ones open [their] eyes (~ in the blink of an eye), (7)</l>
<l>he looked at my waist with [my] form that was unknown from before (9+11d)</l>
<l>and at my dress that was worn away at the borders, dilapidated, (11a-c)</l>
<l>gone the big jewels along with the holes that appeared of old, (10) </l>
<l>the paragon, said “this one is a guest, pitiable he,” (12)</l>
<l>stopped the ongoing time-keeping(?), well (13)</l>
<l>gave [me] roast meat along with toddy that was like an angry snake (14)</l>
<l>[and] removed from me the hell-like drought. (15)</l>
<l>I who befittingly turned when measuring [my] heart (19)</l>
<l>to my father who gave [that] very night (16)</l>
<l>like to a raft killing the destitution of me who did not think of begging (18)</l>
<l>before today and on that former day, (17)</l>
<l>being delighted like at the floodgate of a full pond, (20)</l>
<l>henceforth repeating long[-established] words</l>
<l>[and] appearing at the gate of liberal people where mendicants are not limited </l>
<l>on a single day won’t do for the voice of my little Kiṇai drum. (21-23)  </l>
</lg>
